sec.p:
Applying the GSO algorithm 1 yields effective segmentation results by selecting the seed points and threshold values properly. To summarise, GSO approaches consist of five basic steps: neighbourhood select, luciferin update, computer, decision radius update movement, and moving probability. To a large extent, the fitness value and the early luciferin value dictate the luciferin upgrading phase, as shown in equation~(\ref{eqn1}).
\begin{equation*}
j_{k}(r+1)=(1-\mu) j_{k}(r)+\beta \text { Fitness }\left(v_{l}(r+1)\right)
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

the value of luciferin of glowworm $k$ at time $r$, the luciferin decay constant, the luciferin improvement constant, the position of glowworm $k$ at time ($r+1$), and the fitness value of glowworm $k^{\prime}$ s location at time ($r+1$) are all represented by $v_{l}(r+1)$. During the neighbour choose phase, equation~(\ref{eqn2}) determines which neighbours of glowworm i at time t contain brighter individuals.
\begin{equation*}
P_{k}(r)=\left\{l: b_{k l}(r)<t_{b}^{k}(r); j_{k}(r)<j_{l}(r)\right\}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

Various state-of-the-art quantisation methods cause quantised RNNs to lose accuracy, to be thoroughly examine in this section. To further grasp the inner workings of these quantisation algorithms, utilise LSTM as an example. The LSTM cell, defined by equations (3) - (5), is the fundamental building block.
\begin{equation*}
\begin{gathered}
k_{r}, h_{r}, e_{r}, m_{r}=\sigma\left(Z_{v} v_{r}+d_{v}+Z_{f} f_{r-1}+d_{f}\right) \\
a_{r}=h_{r} * a_{r-1}+k_{r} * e_{r} \\
f_{r}=m_{r} * \sigma\left(a_{r}\right)
\end{gathered}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

Equation~(\ref{eqn6}) represents the fundamental and direct approach of UQ for transforming a full precision value $v$ into a $i$ bit fixed-point representation.
\begin{equation*}
s_{i}(v)=\frac{\operatorname{round}\left[\left(2^{i}-1\right) v\right]}{\left(2^{i}-1\right)}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

Therefore, $v$ must be transformed to [0], [1] before to quantisation and then returned to its original range because this quantisation mainly reduces representation precision instead of changing the dynamic range. The practical UQ is then usually modified according to equation~(\ref{eqn7}).
\begin{equation*}
U Q(V)=2 \max (|V|)\left[s_{i}\left(\frac{V}{2 \max (|V|)}+\frac{1}{2}\right)-\frac{1}{2}\right]
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

This section presents HitNet, which was chosen based on the extensive comparisons made earlier. Activations are directed towards two poles by introducing a constant slope factor into activation, and a hybrid ternary quantisation approach is subsequently applied. In particular, they maximise the benefits of both methods by quantifying weights with TTQ and activations with BTQ. For the hybrid quantisation, equations (8) - (10)are key.
\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
& k_{r}, h_{r}, e_{r}, m_{r}= \sigma\left(T T Q\left(Z_{v}\right) v_{r}+T T Q\left(d_{v}\right)\right. \\
&\left.+T T Q\left(Z_{f}\right) f_{r-1}\right)+T T Q\left(d_{f}\right) \\
& a_{r}=h_{r} * a_{r-1}+k_{r} * e_{r} \\
& f_{r}=B T Q\left(m_{r} * \sigma\left(a_{r}\right)\right)
\end{aligned}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

In order to control the activation distribution, they feed RNN cells a constant slope factor, as shown in equation~(\ref{eqn11}) - (12).
\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
\operatorname{sig} \widehat{m} \operatorname{oid}(v) & =\frac{1}{1+g^{-\frac{v}{\lambda}}} \\
\operatorname{ta} \widehat{n}(f) & =\frac{g^{\frac{v}{\lambda}}-g^{-\frac{v}{\lambda}}}{g^{\frac{v}{\lambda}}+g^{-\frac{v}{\lambda}}}
\end{aligned}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}
